An obvious solution is $ u(x)=\pm x$ corresponding to $c=\mp 1$. Up to a multiplicative dimensional constant, $u$ is the {\it kink} velocity. The solution $ u(x)= + x$ corresponds to the path being systematically {\it kinked outward}, away from the center of the harmonic well. We reject it for being non-physical and retain $ u(x)=- x$.  

All the solutions should share this property of having the path {\it kinked inward}, toward the center of the well in proportion to the distance of the path, at least when $|x|\to\infty$. For this reason, we have looked for solutions in the form of the ratio of two function $ u(x)=P(x)/Q(x)$ such that $\lim_{x\to\pm\infty} u( x)=-x$. Inspired by the work of Hermann \cite{Hermann1997} on the infinite square well, we used Hermite polynomials as the denominator $Q(x)=H_n(x)$. This allows for the path to be {\it kinked away} from the regions where the Hermite polynomials have a root. The solution $ u(x)=- x$ enters this pattern for $n=0$ as $H_0(x)=1$ is the only Hermite polynomial with no roots. The solutions obtained for $n$ in the range from $0$ to $5$ are given in Table \ref{solutions} along with the values of $ c_n$. We did not identify a general expression for the solution for a given $n$. 

The values of $c_n=2n+1$ follow the same patterns as the eigenenergies of a quantum harmonic oscillator. In fact $E_n=mC_n=2m\mathcal D \Omega(n+\frac 12)$ corresponds to the eigenenergies of the quantum harmonic oscillator for the identification $\hbar=2m\mathcal D$. 

We do not prove that all the solutions are such that $c_n=2n+1$. However we can observe how the solutions change when the integration constant $c$ departs from $c_n$. We write $c=c_n+\delta c$ and  $u=u_n+y$. The differential equation gives: $\frac{dy}{d x}+y^2+2 u_n y+\delta c=0$.
Far from the well center, $|x|\gg1$ and $u_n= x$ and we can consider $|y|\ll |u_n|$ so the $y^2$ term can be dropped. With this simplification and 
writing $y=f(x)e^{ x^2}$, it comes $\frac {df}{d x}=-\delta Ce^{- x^2}$ and $f( x)=-\frac{\delta c \sqrt{\pi}}{2}{\rm sign}(x)$ so that $ u( x)\approx- x -\frac{\delta c \sqrt{\pi}}{2}{\rm sign}(x)e^{ x^2}$. In the Langevin equation, the corrective term will be responsible for the path to be either kinked away from the center of the well or kinked toward the center of the well depending on the sign of $\delta c$. The path is either forced toward the center or escapes indefinitely, in both cases departing from our requirement that $\langle V\rangle=0$. This, in itself, is reminding of the fact that when solving the time independent Schr\"odinger equation for the harmonic well, the wave functions can be normalized only for the eigenenergies. 

